# Week 7 — ICS Attack & Anomaly Simulation

## Overview

Week 7 focuses on simulating **industrial cybersecurity incidents** within the ICS-RedSim lab environment.
The purpose of this phase is to generate abnormal network behavior and evaluate whether the deployed monitoring tools can detect suspicious activity.

Controlled scenarios were executed from a testing machine to simulate different types of industrial threats such as reconnaissance activity, command misuse, process manipulation, and availability disruptions.

These scenarios allow the system to demonstrate how **industrial monitoring tools detect abnormal ICS network behavior**.

---

# Objectives

The primary objectives of Week 7 include:

* Simulate controlled ICS security incidents
* Generate abnormal industrial network traffic
* Observe process behavior during incidents
* Capture network evidence
* Validate IDS detection capability

---

# Attack Simulation Environment

Security testing was performed using a dedicated testing machine running **Kali Linux**.

The testing machine was placed in a separate network segment to simulate an external device interacting with the ICS environment.

### Simulation Workflow

```
Attacker Machine
       |
       |
Network Interaction
       |
       v
PLC / SCADA System
       |
       |
Abnormal Network Traffic
       |
       v
Suricata IDS
       |
       v
Security Alerts (Wazuh Dashboard)
```

This setup allows testing of security detection mechanisms in a controlled environment.

---

# Scenario Categories

Multiple incident scenarios were created to simulate different types of ICS threats.

## Category A — Discovery & Misuse

These scenarios simulate reconnaissance activity within the OT network.

| Scenario | Description                       |
| -------- | --------------------------------- |
| A1       | OT Network Scan Attempt           |
| A2       | Unauthorized Modbus Read Burst    |
| A3       | Unauthorized Modbus Write Attempt |

These scenarios represent early-stage attacker activity attempting to identify industrial devices.

---

## Category B — Process Integrity Attacks

These scenarios simulate attempts to manipulate industrial process values.

| Scenario | Description                  |
| -------- | ---------------------------- |
| B1       | Sensor Value Spoofing        |
| B2       | Rapid Command Timing Anomaly |

Such attacks can mislead operators or cause unexpected system behavior.

---

## Category C — Availability Disruptions

These scenarios simulate conditions that disrupt industrial system availability.

| Scenario | Description                           |
| -------- | ------------------------------------- |
| C1       | High Traffic Burst / Flood Simulation |
| C2       | SCADA Service Disruption              |

These events can degrade system performance or temporarily interrupt operations.

---

## Category D — Detection Validation

These scenarios confirm that monitoring tools properly detect abnormal activity.

| Scenario | Description                  |
| -------- | ---------------------------- |
| D1       | IDS Alert Verification       |
| D2       | Incident Evidence Collection |

This phase ensures that security monitoring tools generate alerts during abnormal events.

---

# Evidence Collection

For each scenario, multiple types of evidence were collected.

| Evidence Type   | Source            |
| --------------- | ----------------- |
| Network Packets | Wireshark capture |
| IDS Alerts      | Suricata logs     |
| Security Events | Wazuh dashboard   |
| Process Impact  | SCADA screenshots |

Collecting this evidence allows analysis of how attacks affect the ICS environment.

---

# Observations

During scenario execution, the following observations were made:

* Abnormal traffic patterns appeared in packet captures.
* Suricata generated alerts for suspicious activity.
* Security events were visible in the Wazuh dashboard.
* Some scenarios impacted the simulated industrial process.

These observations demonstrate the effectiveness of the monitoring layer implemented in earlier phases.

